House Price Prediction

https://gist.github.com/satkr7/219ef0497f8cb7f717820508dd97cc10#file-mulitple_models_with_gridsearchcv-ipynb

Predict sales prices¶

Ask a home buyer to describe their dream house, and they probably won't begin with the height of the basement ceiling or the proximity to an east-west railroad. But this playground competition's dataset proves that much more influences price negotiations than the number of bedrooms or a white-picket fence.

With 79 explanatory variables describing (almost) every aspect of residential homes in Ames, Iowa, this competition challenges you to predict the final price of each home.

Goal

It is your job to predict the sales price for each house. For each Id in the test set, you must predict the value of the SalePrice variable.

Metric

Submissions are evaluated on Root-Mean-Squared-Error (RMSE) between the logarithm of the predicted value and the logarithm of the observed sales price. (Taking logs means that errors in predicting expensive houses and cheap houses will affect the result equally.)

Submission File Format

The file should contain a header and have the following format:

Id,SalePrice

1461,169000.1

1462,187724.1233

1463,175221

etc.

Il ne faut pas que je touche le test set.

J'ai vu qu'il avait des données manquantes, mais je dois ne rien toucher pour ne pas faire du data leakage, corrompre mon fichier...

Il faut que je fasse une pipeline dans laquelle je mets tout le feature engineering necessaire au train set et donc par le suite à de nouvelles données (test set).

Il faut que je fasse la même API que j'ai faite pour la détéction de fraudes bancaires.

There are columns that have between 80% and 100% of missing values.

Alley / PoolQC / Fence / MiscFeature

But when I looked about the data description I saw that for some columns there are a value "NA" as an important indicators.

Alley value "NA" means no alley.

PoolQC value "NA" means no pool.

Fence value "NA" means no fence.

MiscFeature value "NA" means there no miscellaneous feature not covered in other categories.

I need to investigate for the other columns with missing values.

LotFrontage --> real missing values

MasVnrType --> real missing values.

MasVnrArea --> real missing values.

BsmtQual value "NA" means no basment.

BsmtCond value "NA" means no basment.

BsmtExposure value "NA" means no basment.

BsmtFinType1 value "NA" means no basment.

BsmtFinType2 value "NA" means no basment.

Electrical --> real missing values.

FireplaceQu value "NA" means no fire place.

GarageType value "NA" means no garage.

GarageYrBlt --> real missing values.

GarageFinish value "NA" means no garage.

GarageQual value "NA" means no garage.

GarageCond value "NA" means no garage.

So, only the columns below have real missing values

I can drop all the value with a correlation under 50.

LotFrontage will be dropped (so, no need to fill it's missing values).

These features are not really relevent for determined and predict the price.

Data Types Modification Tracking¶

-GarageYrBlt needs to be convert into int

-Value with "NA" need to be clarified, for exemple for the feature PoolQC instead of "NA" for no pool, write "No Pool".

-Missing values needs to be filled maybe with the median for the numeric ones and by mode for the object. But a KNNImputer can be more accurate and can be used for all the data types.

Because there are a lot of features (81), it can be interresting to see if we can create combinaison of features, like for exemple kid + teen = children.

But all the features seems to be important and not possible to combine.

I think that the dimentionality reduction like PCA for exemple will be required.

#MasVnrArea
s = train["MasVnrArea"]
q1 = s.quantile(0.25)
q3 = s.quantile(0.75)
iqr = q3 - q1
iqr_lower = q1 - 1.5 * iqr
iqr_upper = q3 + 1.5 * iqr
outliers = dict(s[(s < iqr_lower) | (s > iqr_upper)])

print("MasVnrArea")
print("Lower", iqr_lower)
print("Upper", iqr_upper)
print("Min", train['MasVnrArea'].min())
print("Max", train['MasVnrArea'].max())
print("\n")

Data Modifications
¶

In the train set the features below have no missing values and are int64 type.

-TotalBsmtSF
-GarageCars
-GarageArea

But in test set they have missing values and are in object types.

And they correspond to numerical features and have numericals values.

So, I need to fill the missing values and then to convert them into int64 type.

Like that I will be able to encode them later.

In [662]:
test[['TotalBsmtSF', 'GarageCars', 'GarageArea']] = test[['TotalBsmtSF', 'GarageCars', 'GarageArea']].fillna(test[['TotalBsmtSF', 'GarageCars', 'GarageArea']].median())
In [663]:
test["TotalBsmtSF"] = test["TotalBsmtSF"].astype('int64')
test["GarageCars"] = test["GarageCars"].astype('int64')
test["GarageArea"] = test["GarageArea"].astype('int64')

Drop columns that have a low correlation coefficient.¶

In [665]:
def drop_corr_test(df, target, value):
        corr_matrix = df.corrwith(df[target])
        corr_to_drop = corr_matrix[corr_matrix < value].index
        df.drop(corr_to_drop, axis = 1, inplace = True)

Train / Test Split¶

In [688]:
#438
def train_and_test_split(x, y ,value):
    global xtrain
    global xval
    global ytrain
    global yval
    
    xtrain = x[:value]
    xval = x[value:]
    ytrain = y.iloc[:value]
    yval = y.iloc[value:]
    #return xtrain, xval, ytrain, yval
In [689]:
train_and_test_split(x, y, 438)

dtrs = []

    dtr.fit(xtrain, ytrain)
